Speeder Game

by: Michael Smee

This game was made for my level 2 project at The League of Amazing Programmers.
Click here to download and play!

1. Why I Made This Game

I decided to make this game as I was inspired by playing the Star Wars game battlefront where you would navigate a large speeder through the forest. I thought it would be interesting to make a game that also shared many aspects to league invaders.

2. What I Learned

From user testing, I learned that I had to make changes to some of the formatting for the game. To start, I was told that the bullet should come from a more accurate position from the speeder as it was harder to align it well. I also learned that I needed to change some of my code for resetting the level as it would not always work properly.

3. Architecture of My Game

The different parts of my game were the speeder, the barriers, the enemy, and the bullets, and the background. All aspects of the game took place in the background. I then had the barriers constantly moving in the background with the enemy and looping back around each time they reach the end. I then had the speeder be able to freely move around in any direction, but would die if it touched an enemy or a barrier. Then I had the bullets, which would come out of the speeder when the space bar was pressed and would create a bullet that would move across the screen and would make an enemy go away if it hit one.

4. Technical Implementation

Some of the technical implementations for my game were being able to spawn the enemy inside the barrier boxes. I had to do this by creating a variables for the barriers and setting them apart from each other with a set distance known as the barrier height. Inside of this height, I would then have a randomly generated number which would determine where the alien spawned inside of the barriers.

5. Most Challenging Part

The most challenging part of the project was the hitboxes. This was because of how the enemy would move as well as the speeder. The enemy would move with the projectiles and at the end of each cycle, would spawn in a random position in between the two pipes. Therefor, when the enemy was hit with a bullet, it would not die as its hitbox was paired with the barriers. I was able to eventually fix the problem by being able to recreate the enemies hitbox for different scenarios involving it making contact with either the speeder, or the bullet.

6. Future Fixes and Updates

If I were to improve the game, I would add more variations in the barrier's movement as well as there being a real end to the game such as level 50. I might also try to make the enemies move or be able to fire back at the speeder.
